</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6D837C85102CFFB3DBE2FDC44E202814" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25262F0E102CFFB3DBE2FDC44E202814" blockId="9.[151,1437,150,825]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C102CFFB3DBE2FDC44D012984" bold="true" box="[199,308,655,681]" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D102CFFB3DA61FDC44E1C2984" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[324,553,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamboosielloides">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C102CFFB3DA61FDC44E1C2984" box="[324,553,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">A. bamboosielloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in having the fore wings without duplicated cilia. Moreover, it has very short and V-shaped maxillary stylets (Fig. 36), which are reaching only to the basal collar of the head, like those of 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D102CFFB3DBDFFD9C4DC029DC" box="[250,501,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Bamboosiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C102CFFB3DBDFFD9C4DA129DC" box="[250,404,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Bamboosiella</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
This feature is shared with 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D102CFFB3D817FD9C4FFE29DC" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[818,971,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malayanus">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C102CFFB3D817FD9C4FFE29DC" box="[818,971,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">A. malayanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, newly described below from Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="5D8E6F9E102CFFB3DBB2FDB04D352838" box="[151,256,763,789]" name="Malaysia" pageId="9" pageNumber="110">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, but that species can easily be distinguished by the unicolourous brown body and the presence of the duplicated cilia on the fore wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
